  <head>
    <title>Unlikely Existence of God</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Unlikely Existence of God</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:kakadoo@sprynet.com">Amanda</a> on December 26, 1996 at 18:46:35:<p>
This posting is a continuation of an issue discussed regarding atheism/agnosticism where I claimed that there was evidence that the existence of God was unlikely. Lynn was curious as to what this evidence was so off the top of my head I'll attempt to list that which I've come across but I'm sure other people here will have more to add and of course arguments on anything that I state are more than welcome.<br>First, let me state that over the years many definitions of God have been invented and I basically see it as an attempt made by theists to cover their ass with the discoveries made by science. With space exploration we have discovered there are no anomolies in our solar system of an entity that could be God or of the heavens referred to in various bibles. You would think that no matter how different this entity was from a human - even taking into consideration the ideas of other possible dimensions and planes of existence there would be SOMETHING; whether chemical or physical or following the natural laws that would show a change from other findings.<br>Second, after Darwin found a mechanism to explain how man evolved along with other animals that over the years has accumulated much evidence for it then the whole idea of creation was seriously reconsidered by all intelligent humans. Most have given up the idea of creation completely.<br>Third, if we trace the history of religion we can understand how it might have been invented and it is completely justified to those times - nomads who could be considered the first Homos are said to have worshipped the "old man" of the tribe as he was wise and capable of magic - this later evolved into an old man myth. The first human civilizatons with more leisure time to ponder the mysteries of the world chalked all natural phenomena to a higher being. Curiosity is definately a strong trait in humans and without any knowledge of the way the world works, I really can understand why one might think that thunder and floods and disease etc.. were produced by something with a purpose. Right up until the Enlightenment I can see why the religious beliefs were deemed more realistic and rational than any others - though that didn't warrant all the great minds that were silenced. <br>Then if you look at the big religions; christianity, judaism and Islam, you can see that a lot of their material was borrowed from other existing religions of the time. Most of the key concepts - heaven, salvation, judgement day, good vs evil etc... were already being discussed. One of the purposes of religion has always been to control the herd and through fear and clever propoganda this was acheived. It's fairly likely Jesus existed (and Mohommed too for that matter) and it can be thought that a few of their teachings were admirable but there is no evidence that they were anything more then men. There is no evidence for the miracles of both the Old and New Testaments. (I haven't read the Koran yet so I'm not sure if miracles happened in it).<br>What else? Hmmm...<br>The big argument atheists used at the dawn of this century was that "if there is a God why is all this suffering going on" - that's been explained away now by theists but still - considering God was mighty pissed when the first humans he created got a little out of hand, you'd think we would have all been drowned long ago for our "sins".<br>I'll leave it at that before I get carried away but there is much more if you're interested, Lynn.<p>Amanda <br>
<br>
