  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Tyler on January 02, 1997 at 14:41:14:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="608.html">Re: Unlikely Existence of God</a> posted by Lynn on December 28, 1996 at 10:08:42:<p>
: Dear Amanda,<p>: Obviously I disagree with you.  I could take every argument you make and turn it around to prove my own point, but I doubt if I could convince you.  There is only one way to know for sure if God is real.  <p>================================<br>First you would have to accept the possibility that there is a God.  Then you would have to open you mind and heart and sincerely humble yourself before Him and just say "God, if you are there would you please reveal yourself to me?"  You'd have to have the right attitude and little persistence, but I guarantee if you "keep knocking the door will be opened".<p>I cannot let this argument stand because your conclusion is in your premise.  I'd have to accept existence, then request revelation?  It seems to me that in doing so, I cannot remain wholly objective anymore.<p>Incidentally, the use of the word "existence" when describing God was dispensed with by Immanuel Kant.  He made a very convincing case for rejecting the use of the word as a predicate (the reasoning is contained in "A Critique of Pure Reason", if you'd like to know more about it.<br>
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
