Subject: <input type=text name="subject"value="Re: Unlikely Existence of God" size=50><p>
Comments:<br>
<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: : Dear Amanda,

: : Obviously I disagree with you.  I could take every argument you make and turn it around to prove my own point, but I doubt if I could convince you.  There is only one way to know for sure if God is real.  

: ================================
: First you would have to accept the possibility that there is a God.  Then you would have to open you mind and heart and sincerely humble yourself before Him and just say &quot;God, if you are there would you please reveal yourself to me?&quot;  You'd have to have the right attitude and little persistence, but I guarantee if you &quot;keep knocking the door will be opened&quot;.

: I cannot let this argument stand because your conclusion is in your premise.  I'd have to accept existence, then request revelation?  It seems to me that in doing so, I cannot remain wholly objective anymore.

: Incidentally, the use of the word &quot;existence&quot; when describing God was dispensed with by Immanuel Kant.  He made a very convincing case for rejecting the use of the word as a predicate (the reasoning is contained in &quot;A Critique of Pure Reason&quot;, if you'd like to know more about it.

</textarea>
