<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Amanda on December 29, 1996 at 10:27:17:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="608.html">Re: Unlikely Existence of God</a> posted by Lynn on December 28, 1996 at 10:08:42:<p>
<br>: : This posting is a continuation of an issue discussed regarding atheism/agnosticism where I claimed that there was evidence that the existence of God was unlikely. Lynn was curious as to what this evidence was so off the top of my head I'll attempt to list that which I've come across but I'm sure other people here will have more to add and of course arguments on anything that I state are more than welcome.<br>: : First, let me state that over the years many definitions of God have been invented and I basically see it as an attempt made by theists to cover their ass with the discoveries made by science. With space exploration we have discovered there are no anomolies in our solar system of an entity that could be God or of the heavens referred to in various bibles. You would think that no matter how different this entity was from a human - even taking into consideration the ideas of other possible dimensions and planes of existence there would be SOMETHING; whether chemical or physical or following the natural laws that would show a change from other findings.<br>: : Second, after Darwin found a mechanism to explain how man evolved along with other animals that over the years has accumulated much evidence for it then the whole idea of creation was seriously reconsidered by all intelligent humans. Most have given up the idea of creation completely.<br>: : Third, if we trace the history of religion we can understand how it might have been invented and it is completely justified to those times - nomads who could be considered the first Homos are said to have worshipped the "old man" of the tribe as he was wise and capable of magic - this later evolved into an old man myth. The first human civilizatons with more leisure time to ponder the mysteries of the world chalked all natural phenomena to a higher being. Curiosity is definately a strong trait in humans and without any knowledge of the way the world works, I really can understand why one might think that thunder and floods and disease etc.. were produced by something with a purpose. Right up until the Enlightenment I can see why the religious beliefs were deemed more realistic and rational than any others - though that didn't warrant all the great minds that were silenced. <br>: : Then if you look at the big religions; christianity, judaism and Islam, you can see that a lot of their material was borrowed from other existing religions of the time. Most of the key concepts - heaven, salvation, judgement day, good vs evil etc... were already being discussed. One of the purposes of religion has always been to control the herd and through fear and clever propoganda this was acheived. It's fairly likely Jesus existed (and Mohommed too for that matter) and it can be thought that a few of their teachings were admirable but there is no evidence that they were anything more then men. There is no evidence for the miracles of both the Old and New Testaments. (I haven't read the Koran yet so I'm not sure if miracles happened in it).<br>: : What else? Hmmm...<br>: : The big argument atheists used at the dawn of this century was that "if there is a God why is all this suffering going on" - that's been explained away now by theists but still - considering God was mighty pissed when the first humans he created got a little out of hand, you'd think we would have all been drowned long ago for our "sins".<br>: : I'll leave it at that before I get carried away but there is much more if you're interested, Lynn.<p>: : Amanda <p>: <br>: Dear Amanda,<p>: Obviously I disagree with you.  I could take every argument you make and turn it around to prove my own point, but I doubt if I could convince you.  There is only one way to know for sure if God is real.  First you would have to accept the possibility that there is a God.  Then you would have to open you mind and heart and sincerely humble yourself before Him and just say "God, if you are there would you please reveal yourself to me?"  You'd have to have the right attitude and little persistence, but I guarantee if you "keep knocking the door will be opened".  I suspect that most people at this site would find that to be a very hard thing to do, since, even if there is a God, he has already been judged to be cruel, uncaring, judgemental,...pick your own adjective.  <p>I expected that much but please, show me where you disagree - if I see your point, I'd be more than willing to throw out that argument in the future. You sound like a very kind person and please note that I am not attacking you personally for your beliefs but I must admit - I make a living in attacking beliefs such as yours. My beliefs about religion are very strong though I do try to keep an open mind on the subject and if ever something occured to raise doubt in my mind or if my beliefs were ever shown to be wrong then I would happily change them - I would have no qualms in admitting I was wrong. Skepticism is to me a necessary trait to posess but in the issue regarding religion I am probably more than just a skeptic. Not only do I dibelieve in the various gods and goddesses that have been said to exist in the past but I strongly feel that religion is harmful - I don't enjoy debating with a theist anymore about whether the Christian God exists or not because it is a question that will never be answered.     From all that you have said, it seems that within you, you have found something that allows you to live a more fulfilling life and I am glad for you in that respect but I can't see how that something has to be defined as the God of the bible - perhaps it is just YOU who is responsible for the added happiness and strength that you posess. It appears that most people who claim to be religious i this day and age seem to have similar feelings as you - I think science and enlightenment and the onslaught of freethinkers have been the things responsible for such a change and I think these factors will produce many other "good" changes in the future but again, I see no need for Gods to be brought into the picture. Do you not think we would be better off in believing in things that we can see - things that are natural - things that are realistic? Do you not think that if we would give up the ideas that the suffereing seen on this planet is due to our sins and that salvation will not come until we die we might         possibly be able to deal with the issues a bit better? I'm sure you're aware of the many "bad" things that have happened in the past as a result of religion - how a woman can be a christian is a question I have asked myself time and time again. We can still see today how religion is harmful though I do admit it is not as harmful as it once was. The suppression of science is to me probably the most obvious harm - the amount of ignorance we see in this country especially is another - the hand that the church plays in politics, education, economy, soceity are others. So not only am I claiming that the existence of God is unlikely but I'm claiming that it will most likely be the cause of our demise. I'm not a fanatic about this as it no doubt appears here - but without writing a novel it is very difficult to explain myself fully. I'm still curious though as to how you might turn my arguments around as to the unlikeliness of God. My favorite argument though I realize it is a bit weak was said by Bertrand Russell - "if God existed and was the perfect being he is claimed to be, could he not produce something better than Hitler, Stalin and the Ku Klux Klan?" 
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
