  <head>
    <title>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Tyler on January 02, 1997 at 15:37:43:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="623.html">Re: Unlikely Existence of God</a> posted by Amanda on December 29, 1996 at 10:27:17:<p>
:Do you not think we would be better off in believing in things that we can see - things that are natural - things that are realistic? <p>	Be careful about this sort of talk.  What you describe, if I understand your words correctly, leaves out theoretical exercises.  What of atomic theory? Surely on the scale of our existence, it was once thought, these things are not worthy of out attention.  Now it's the quantum, and the two relativity theories?  Most undeniably, relativity has no applications to our slothly motions.  It does assist us in astrophysics, but that also is a pragmatists thorn.  Pure mathematicians do not deal in the tangible, the visible, the mundane.  What they do now may become applied mathematics in the future, but today it is absolute abstraction.  AND there remains a large body of work that is centuries old but has no applications.  This would bring us to the fine arts and music.  Neither deal much with the tangible or mundane; they are in the realm of transcendence and ineffability.  Both give us glimpses behind, through, or outside the human experience.  Should these not be persued?  I'm more that a little curious about your outlook!<p>============================<p><br>:The suppression of science is to me probably the most obvious harm - the amount of ignorance we see in this country especially is another - the hand that the church plays in politics, education, economy, soceity are others. <p>	Bravo!  Exactly as I'd have stated it.  I am reminded of some research that I had done on American media history.  The movie censorship code was initiated when film became more of an influence on society (early '20's).  When religious zealots got going on the subject, there was harm done to artistic creativity.  I question, by my current standards, the wisdom of using religion as a template for moral and ethical conduct.  One need look no further than the three Crusades, N. Ireland, the Middle East or Jimmy Bakker to see the insensibilities exhibited in the name of religion.  The Production Code forwarded by the religious community were very specific in their directives.  It mentioned great painting and music as morally uplifting art, and indecent books and unclean paintings as degenerate art. <br>Well..... WHAT?  Did any of those people enjoy VanGogh's vision, which was considered heretical in its day?  Did James Joyce err in penning _Ulysses_?  Which art is uplifting?  Point to some.  Why?  Is it, by definition, universally uplifting because certain individuals find it so?  Who will be the art "experts"?  The clergy, who as a group are unqualified for this assignment?  Who will "make" the artists?  Whenever religious institutions get involved in policy beyond their venue, there is rampant silliness, and above all, stunted intellectual growth for the individual and society.  This sounds harsher than I really feel about it, but the case must be made.  Please note that my sharp words are not directed at the idea of religion.  One must ignore dumb, dogmatic people in any circumstance, but rather is aimed at the viral INSTITUTION which, as with any other group, has an agenda.  But is is frequently mean-spirited and insensitive.  That's all.  I'm done.
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
