  <head>
    <title>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Jason on December 28, 1996 at 14:26:42:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="608.html">Re: Unlikely Existence of God</a> posted by Lynn on December 28, 1996 at 10:08:42:<p>
<br>: <br>: Dear Amanda,<p>: Obviously I disagree with you.  I could take every argument you make and turn it around to prove my own point, but I doubt if I could convince you.  There is only one way to know for sure if God is real.  First you would have to accept the possibility that there is a God.  Then you would have to open you mind and heart and sincerely humble yourself before Him and just say "God, if you are there would you please reveal yourself to me?"  You'd have to have the right attitude and little persistence, but I guarantee if you "keep knocking the door will be opened".  I suspect that most people at this site would find that to be a very hard thing to do, since, even if there is a God, he has already been judged to be cruel, uncaring, judgemental,...pick your own adjective.  <p><br>Hi Lynn,<p>I'm relatively new to this message board and I'd like to comment on your response to<br>Amanda. I don't know if you read it yet but I also responded to your post on Big Bang<br>cosmology.<p>The argument you made is similar to the "Skeptic's Prayer" argument made by Peter Kreeft<br>in his book, "Handbook of Christian Apologetics." For a good response to the Skeptic's<br>Prayer, I recommend http://www.infidel.org/library/modern/robby_berry/skeprayr.html.<br>A similar approach can also be found in the Book of Mormon:<p>     "And when ye shall receive these things, I would exhort you that<br>     ye would ask God, the Eternal Father, in the name of Christ, if<br>     these things are not true; and if ye shall ask with a sincere<br>     heart, with real intent, having faith in Christ, he will manifest<br>     the truth of it unto you, by the power of the Holy Ghost."<br>     (Moroni 10:4)<p>Devout Mormons call this "Moroni's Challenge" and they see this as a way of converting<br>non-Mormons.<p>I think there are problems with this sort of argumentation. For an analogy, let's say a<br>boy came up to you with a small box. Let's say he told that he has a fairy inside the<br>box. You open it and you find it's empty. The boy replies that you must ask the fairy<br>to manifest itself first. You do this but still no fairy. The boy says you must do it <br>the correct way. You have to remove all your doubt first, or maybe give the box a<br>little shake, or perhaps caress and kiss the box, then maybe the fairy will appear. If<br>nothing happens then there's something you're doing wrong.<p>The problem here is a lack of testability. What constitutes an answer? This method of <br>contacting a metaphysical being is reduced to ambiguity and confusion. Let's say I <br>make this prayer and I find a $20 bill on the sidewalk. Is it divine intervention<br>or was I just lucky? Or let's say I get into a car accident next week. Was God trying<br>to tell me something or could it be that Canadian roads in the winter can get pretty<br>slippery? In addition, what particular religious entity should I pray to if I want to<br>know if it exists? Why should I accept your deity instead of opting for Moroni's<br>Challenge? And I'm sure that other religions have their own version of the Skeptic's<br>Prayer and Moroni's Challenge too. This is like the fairy in the box analogy except<br>some boys come along and say they see a small dragon, others see an elf, and a few<br>even see Daffy Duck. Which boy should I believe?<p>Finally, for the smoking gun, I did do something like you mentioned twice a few years<br>back. Nothing out of the ordinary happened to me. Of course, I'm sure you can argue <br>that I had the wrong attitude or I wasn't sincere enough, but then I'll have to point<br>the boy with the fairy in the box analogy.<p>By the way, I hope I don't seem condescending to you or anything. Please understand I<br>don't mean any offense. I try to write as if we were having a polite intellectual<br>conversation but sometimes I might present myself different than I intended to.<br>- Jason
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
