: : 
: : Dear Amanda,

: : Obviously I disagree with you.  I could take every argument you make and turn it around to prove my own point, but I doubt if I could convince you.  There is only one way to know for sure if God is real.  First you would have to accept the possibility that there is a God.  Then you would have to open you mind and heart and sincerely humble yourself before Him and just say &quot;God, if you are there would you please reveal yourself to me?&quot;  You'd have to have the right attitude and little persistence, but I guarantee if you &quot;keep knocking the door will be opened&quot;.  I suspect that most people at this site would find that to be a very hard thing to do, since, even if there is a God, he has already been judged to be cruel, uncaring, judgemental,...pick your own adjective.  

: 
: Hi Lynn,

: I'm relatively new to this message board and I'd like to comment on your response to
: Amanda. I don't know if you read it yet but I also responded to your post on Big Bang
: cosmology.

: The argument you made is similar to the &quot;Skeptic's Prayer&quot; argument made by Peter Kreeft
: in his book, &quot;Handbook of Christian Apologetics.&quot; For a good response to the Skeptic's
: Prayer, I recommend http://www.infidel.org/library/modern/robby_berry/skeprayr.html.
: A similar approach can also be found in the Book of Mormon:

:      &quot;And when ye shall receive these things, I would exhort you that
:      ye would ask God, the Eternal Father, in the name of Christ, if
:      these things are not true; and if ye shall ask with a sincere
:      heart, with real intent, having faith in Christ, he will manifest
:      the truth of it unto you, by the power of the Holy Ghost.&quot;
:      (Moroni 10:4)

: Devout Mormons call this &quot;Moroni's Challenge&quot; and they see this as a way of converting
: non-Mormons.

: I think there are problems with this sort of argumentation. For an analogy, let's say a
: boy came up to you with a small box. Let's say he told that he has a fairy inside the
: box. You open it and you find it's empty. The boy replies that you must ask the fairy
: to manifest itself first. You do this but still no fairy. The boy says you must do it 
: the correct way. You have to remove all your doubt first, or maybe give the box a
: little shake, or perhaps caress and kiss the box, then maybe the fairy will appear. If
: nothing happens then there's something you're doing wrong.

: The problem here is a lack of testability. What constitutes an answer? This method of 
: contacting a metaphysical being is reduced to ambiguity and confusion. Let's say I 
: make this prayer and I find a $20 bill on the sidewalk. Is it divine intervention
: or was I just lucky? Or let's say I get into a car accident next week. Was God trying
: to tell me something or could it be that Canadian roads in the winter can get pretty
: slippery? In addition, what particular religious entity should I pray to if I want to
: know if it exists? Why should I accept your deity instead of opting for Moroni's
