: Dear Jason,

: I am not offended at all.  

: I don't necessarily think your prayer has been unanswered.  God works in His own time and His own way.  I believe that seeds that were planted when I was a child did not come to fruition until my early 20's.  One thing I know is that he always answers my prayers, but never in the way I hoped.  It's always better than any solution I could have concocted.  

: I can't prove or explain to you what it is like to have a relationship with God.  It is something you simply have to experience.  I also don't think anyone saved or unsaved should jump to conclusions about whether a windfall or a tragedy is something that has been &quot;done to them&quot; by God.  Some things just happen by chance, but God always uses these events for the spiritual benefit of those who love him.  

: You say I'm presenting you with an invisible fairy in a box, well, I would use the analogy that you and I are on a trek through a rugged wilderness.  We're existing on nuts, berries, and bugs, and have no clothes to wear,when I discover a magnificent banquet table full of every kind of food.  I try to convince you to come have a taste, yet you, feeling proud of your self-sufficiency, (and finding it hard to believe in the first place) refuse to come with me to the table or even to admit that it exists.  I feel terrible that I have discovered something so wonderful and can't share it with you, as I watch you struggling and sweating your way through the briars and bushes, not knowing where you're headed or why you've taken the journey.

: I was once an agnostic from an agnostic/atheist family.  I have felt the way you feel and made the same arguments that have been made on the page.  I'm not a kook or a bible thumper.  I don't even go to church, but I love Jesus and I know he loves me.  He is a great source of quiet joy for me, and has taught me much about how to live my life to the fullest. 

: You seem to have a tender heart, Jason.  I'm confident your prayer will be answered.

</textarea>
<p>
