  <head>
    <title>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Jason on December 29, 1996 at 03:37:55:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="611.html">Re: Unlikely Existence of God</a> posted by Lynn on December 28, 1996 at 16:05:59:<p>
<p><br>: <br>: Dear Jason,<p>: I am not offended at all.  <p>: I don't necessarily think your prayer has been unanswered.  God works in His own time and His own way.  I believe that seeds that were planted when I was a child did not come to fruition until my early 20's.  One thing I know is that he always answers my prayers, but never in the way I hoped.  It's always better than any solution I could have concocted.  <p>: I can't prove or explain to you what it is like to have a relationship with God.  It is something you simply have to experience.  I also don't think anyone saved or unsaved should jump to conclusions about whether a windfall or a tragedy is something that has been "done to them" by God.  Some things just happen by chance, but God always uses these events for the spiritual benefit of those who love him.  <p>: You say I'm presenting you with an invisible fairy in a box, well, I would use the analogy that you and I are on a trek through a rugged wilderness.  We're existing on nuts, berries, and bugs, and have no clothes to wear,when I discover a magnificent banquet table full of every kind of food.  I try to convince you to come have a taste, yet you, feeling proud of your self-sufficiency, (and finding it hard to believe in the first place) refuse to come with me to the table or even to admit that it exists.  I feel terrible that I have discovered something so wonderful and can't share it with you, as I watch you struggling and sweating your way through the briars and bushes, not knowing where you're headed or why you've taken the journey.<p><br>Interesting analogy. I'm quite familiar with Christian theology in this regard. A<br>similar analogy I heard went like this: "Christians aren't superior to anyone<br>else, we're simply beggars telling other beggars where they can find food." I<br>appreciate the thought behind this way of thinking. I know that you're concerned<br>for my spiritual well being. However, although I can respect your religious <br>beliefs, I cannot embrace them. If one day I find out that you are right and I'm <br>wrong, I'll be quite surprised, but I'll happily embrace the truth whatever it may<br>be. However, at this time I don't think your religious beliefs stand up to the<br>tests of reason and logic.<p>I think there are a few problems with your analogy. If I was in this hypothetical<br>forest with you, you would be able to show me physical evidence of the banquet <br>table. You could bring me the tablecloth or show me the cutlery. If you did this,<br>I'd be more than happy to dine with you. Unfortunately, it's a little tough to do<br>this with a deity who likes to play hide and seek.  Second, I've got a thousand<br>other different people telling me that they have "the One True Banquet Table" and<br>that everybody else will lead me astray. Why should I choose your banquet table <br>over the Mormon's table, or the Muslim's table, or the Bahai's table, or <br>Zoroastrian's, or Buddhist's, or Hindu's, or Sikhs's, etc., etc.....?    <p>: I was once an agnostic from an agnostic/atheist family.  I have felt the way you feel and made the same arguments that have been made on the page.  I'm not a kook or a bible thumper.  I don't even go to church, but I love Jesus and I know he loves me.  He is a great source of quiet joy for me, and has taught me much about how to live my life to the fullest. <p><br>Personally, I was raised in a non-practicing Anglican family. My doubts and<br>skepticism of religion began in my university years, which eventually led to my<br>rejection of religion. It's good that you're happy. I would also like to learn <br>how to live life to its fullest (I admit that I'm still trying to figure this <br>out) but I don't think happiness is dependent on one's metaphysical beliefs. I've<br>known of very happy and unhappy people who are religious or nonreligious. I seek <br>happiness but I also want to make sure I'm living in reality as well.<br>- Jason<br>
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
