Comments:<br>
<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>

: 
: : 
: : : 
: : : Dear Jason,

: : : I am not offended at all.  

: : : I don't necessarily think your prayer has been unanswered.  God works in His own time and His own way.  I believe that seeds that were planted when I was a child did not come to fruition until my early 20's.  One thing I know is that he always answers my prayers, but never in the way I hoped.  It's always better than any solution I could have concocted.  

: : : I can't prove or explain to you what it is like to have a relationship with God.  It is something you simply have to experience.  I also don't think anyone saved or unsaved should jump to conclusions about whether a windfall or a tragedy is something that has been &quot;done to them&quot; by God.  Some things just happen by chance, but God always uses these events for the spiritual benefit of those who love him.  

: : : You say I'm presenting you with an invisible fairy in a box, well, I would use the analogy that you and I are on a trek through a rugged wilderness.  We're existing on nuts, berries, and bugs, and have no clothes to wear,when I discover a magnificent banquet table full of every kind of food.  I try to convince you to come have a taste, yet you, feeling proud of your self-sufficiency, (and finding it hard to believe in the first place) refuse to come with me to the table or even to admit that it exists.  I feel terrible that I have discovered something so wonderful and can't share it with you, as I watch you struggling and sweating your way through the briars and bushes, not knowing where you're headed or why you've taken the journey.

: : 
: : Interesting analogy. I'm quite familiar with Christian theology in this regard. A
: : similar analogy I heard went like this: &quot;Christians aren't superior to anyone
: : else, we're simply beggars telling other beggars where they can find food.&quot; I
: : appreciate the thought behind this way of thinking. I know that you're concerned
: : for my spiritual well being. However, although I can respect your religious 
: : beliefs, I cannot embrace them. If one day I find out that you are right and I'm 
: : wrong, I'll be quite surprised, but I'll happily embrace the truth whatever it may
: : be. However, at this time I don't think your religious beliefs stand up to the
: : tests of reason and logic.

: : I think there are a few problems with your analogy. If I was in this hypothetical
: : forest with you, you would be able to show me physical evidence of the banquet 
: : table. You could bring me the tablecloth or show me the cutlery. If you did this,
: : I'd be more than happy to dine with you. Unfortunately, it's a little tough to do
: : this with a deity who likes to play hide and seek.  Second, I've got a thousand
: : other different people telling me that they have &quot;the One True Banquet Table&quot; and
: : that everybody else will lead me astray. Why should I choose your banquet table 
: : over the Mormon's table, or the Muslim's table, or the Bahai's table, or 
: : Zoroastrian's, or Buddhist's, or Hindu's, or Sikhs's, etc., etc.....?    

: : : I was once an agnostic from an agnostic/atheist family.  I have felt the way you feel and made the same arguments that have been made on the page.  I'm not a kook or a bible thumper.  I don't even go to church, but I love Jesus and I know he loves me.  He is a great source of quiet joy for me, and has taught me much about how to live my life to the fullest. 

: : 
: : Personally, I was raised in a non-practicing Anglican family. My doubts and
: : skepticism of religion began in my university years, which eventually led to my
: : rejection of religion. It's good that you're happy. I would also like to learn 
: : how to live life to its fullest (I admit that I'm still trying to figure this 
: : out) but I don't think happiness is dependent on one's metaphysical beliefs. I've
: : known of very happy and unhappy people who are religious or nonreligious. I seek 
: : happiness but I also want to make sure I'm living in reality as well.
: : - Jason

: Dear Jason,

: I believe that it is possible in our lifetime that you will get the proof you need that there is indeed a spiritual realm to this world.  Unfortunately, the next person to come to earth performing signs and wonders will be the AntiChrist.  Those with very strong anti-christian feelings will probably follow right along when our persecution begins.  Perhaps if it does occur, you'll remember that I told you this.

: When you turn a key in a lock and it opens the door, you must assume you have selected the right one.  I have tested the teachings of the Bible and found them to be true in every situation.  My relationships and my general well being really hum along when I keep my nose in the scriptures.  When I get lazy and forget to read and pray, the next thing I know, everything is getting screwed up again.  Whether there is a God or not, there is no denying that living by the teachings found in His word are highly beneficial.
: I'm not perfect by any stretch of the imagination, but I'm a much better and happier person than I used to be.  I was a mess, and I have no problem with giving the credit to the Lord for reaching in and pulling me out of the muck.
: If you have any part of scripture that you would like to debate that doesn't require me to have a knowledge of geology, I'd LOVE to give you my views.


