  <head>
    <title>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:nosferat@auracom.com">Stephen Charchuk</a> on December 29, 1996 at 00:59:18:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="611.html">Re: Unlikely Existence of God</a> posted by Lynn on December 28, 1996 at 16:05:59:<p>
: I don't necessarily think your prayer has been unanswered.  God works in His own time and His own way.  I believe that seeds that were planted when I was a child did not come to fruition until my early 20's.  One thing I know is that he always answers my prayers, but never in the way I hoped.  It's always better than any solution I could have concocted.  <p>It all depends on what one asks for, if one prays to wake up in the morning it is a very good chance that one will.<p>: I can't prove or explain to you what it is like to have a relationship with God.  It is something you simply have to experience.  I also don't think anyone saved or unsaved should jump to conclusions about whether a windfall or a tragedy is something that has been "done to them" by God.  Some things just happen by chance, but God always uses these events for the spiritual benefit of those who love him.  <p>That is like saying that in order to prove, or explain, death one has to die. Hey, Mr. Spock. <g><p>: You say I'm presenting you with an invisible fairy in a box, well, I would use the analogy that you and I are on a trek through a rugged wilderness.  We're existing on nuts, berries, and bugs, and have no clothes to wear,when I discover a magnificent banquet table full of every kind of food.  I try to convince you to come have a taste, yet you, feeling proud of your self-sufficiency, (and finding it hard to believe in the first place) refuse to come with me to the table or even to admit that it exists.  I feel terrible that I have discovered something so wonderful and can't share it with you, as I watch you struggling and sweating your way through the briars and bushes, not knowing where you're headed or why you've taken the journey.<p>Your analogy could be used by any religion in the world. Yours is not the only feast out there.<p>: I was once an agnostic from an agnostic/atheist family.  I have felt the way you feel and made the same arguments that have been made on the page.  I'm not a kook or a bible thumper.  I don't even go to church, but I love Jesus and I know he loves me.  He is a great source of quiet joy for me, and has taught me much about how to live my life to the fullest. <p>I, for one, started out the other way and finally came to my own views and my life is full and rich as well.<br>
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
