    <center>
      <h1>Re: P.S.</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:Nosferat@auracom.com">Stephen Charchuk</a> on December 18, 1996 at 16:24:26:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="543.html">Re: P.S.</a> posted by Lynn on December 17, 1996 at 22:42:22:<p>
<br>: I doubt if his opinions mean much to you either.  I have not made up my mind yet about evolution, but reguardless of my final conclusion it won't change my belief in God.<p>Even he said that he still believes that the sould is a creation of his god. <p>: Everyone who believes in evolution seems pretty sure of the Big Bang theory, and is quick to point out that people like myself who believe the universe was created by God are basing the theory on irrational thoughts and emotions.  I am merely pointing out that one theory can be as irrational as another.  I'm still waiting for documented evidence that chaos evolves into order of it's own accord.  Can anyone help me?<p>Evolution is based on rationality and logic. Creationism is based on what they wanted it to be without any real, or objectively observed facts. The Big Bang is a fact, the question is what came before it.<p>: I am aware of the differences between a clock and the universe.  It was merely an analogy. <p>A better analogy would be that of a living organism and not of an artifical construct.<p>Try out this site for more detail on both sides of the issue. It includes views from the moderate to the extreme of both.<br>
<br>
<ul><li><a href="http://www.xnet.com/~blatura/left_hem.shtml">The Left Hemisphere</a></ul>
