      <h1>Re: P.S.</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:lgrant@netonecom.net">Lynn</a> on December 17, 1996 at 22:42:22:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="542.html">Re: P.S.</a> posted by Stephen Charchuk on December 17, 1996 at 16:18:08:<p>
<br>: I don't mean to offend anyone, but the Pope's opinions don't carry that much weight with me.<p>: But he does speak for the largest denomination of Christians (Around 800,000,000 or so Roman Catholics) and that does carry much weight.<p>I doubt if his opinions mean much to you either.  I have not made up my mind yet about evolution, but reguardless of my final conclusion it won't change my belief in God.<p>: : If you can offer me a scientific study that has shown that chaos, of it's own accord, ascends to a state of ordered complexity, I'll shut up.<p>: No one can know for sure how the universe had started, not even those who claim it was done by a creator. The only way to know for sure is to die.<p>Everyone who believes in evolution seems pretty sure of the Big Bang theory, and is quick to point out that people like myself who believe the universe was created by God are basing the theory on irrational thoughts and emotions.  I am merely pointing out that one theory can be as irrational as another.  I'm still waiting for documented evidence that chaos evolves into order of it's own accord.  Can anyone help me?<p>: : The living organism theory is interesting.  I've always pondered whether the universe is a mechanism akin to a clock......one that is winding down, I might add.<p>: A clock is an artifical construct, the Universe is a natural one. The Universe is still expanding, so we may still be in the early stage in its life cycle.<p>I am aware of the differences between a clock and the universe.  It was merely an analogy. 
