  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: P.S.</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:lgrant@netonecom.net">Lynn</a> on December 18, 1996 at 19:42:46:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="548.html">Re: P.S.</a> posted by Stephen Charchuk on December 18, 1996 at 16:24:26:<p>
<p>: <br>: : I doubt if his opinions mean much to you either.  I have not made up my mind yet about evolution, but reguardless of my final conclusion it won't change my belief in God.<p>: Even he said that he still believes that the sould is a creation of his god. <p>: : Everyone who believes in evolution seems pretty sure of the Big Bang theory, and is quick to point out that people like myself who believe the universe was created by God are basing the theory on irrational thoughts and emotions.  I am merely pointing out that one theory can be as irrational as another.  I'm still waiting for documented evidence that chaos evolves into order of it's own accord.  Can anyone help me?<p>: Evolution is based on rationality and logic. Creationism is based on what they wanted it to be without any real, or objectively observed facts. The Big Bang is a fact, the question is what came before it.<p><br>Not so fast!<br>Evolution:  the DOCTRINE that all forms of life originated by descent, with gradual or abrupt modifications, from preexisting forms which themselves trace backward in a continuing series to the most rudimentary organisms.<br>Big Bang:  astronomical THEORY that the universe began in a single, gigantic explosion of flammable gases<br>As you can see, we are dealing with BELIEFS which are based both on evidence and conjecture, which, even if proven true, do not explain how these gases, from which all the universe is comprised, came into being.  Nor does it deal with the obvious problem of how the resulting solid particles, hurling through space from the explosion ordered themselves into a complex universe.  I cannot think of a single instance of this ever happening in nature.  <br>I also do not know of any evidence of an observable mutation that ever resulted in a superior creature.  I realize that we have dominant and recessive genes that allow us to adapt to our surroundings, resulting in changes in color, etc., but in order for a new species to evolve from an old one, there must be mutation.<br>Haven't the processes always been the same, or did nature do a 180 at some point?  If in the distant past, order ascended from chaos, and mutation was once a good thing, then everything is working in  reverse now.     <br>: I am aware of the differences between a clock and the universe.  It was merely an analogy. <p>: A better analogy would be that of a living organism and not of an artifical construct.<p>: Try out this site for more detail on both sides of the issue. It includes views from the moderate to the extreme of both.<p><br>
