<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: 
: : Not so fast!
: : Evolution:  the DOCTRINE that all forms of life originated by descent, with gradual or abrupt modifications, from preexisting forms which themselves trace backward in a continuing series to the most rudimentary organisms.

: Doctrine applies to religion and politics, not science. 

: : Big Bang:  astronomical THEORY that the universe began in a single, gigantic explosion of flammable gases

: Theory: 2. A formulation of underlying principles of certain observed phenomena which has been verified to some degree.

: It is no longer a theory.

: You're thinking of a hypothesis. Many get the two mixed up.

: : As you can see, we are dealing with BELIEFS which are based both on evidence and conjecture, which, even if proven true, do not explain how these gases, from which all the universe is comprised, came into being.  Nor does it deal with the obvious problem of how the resulting solid particles, hurling through space from the explosion ordered themselves into a complex universe.  I cannot think of a single instance of this ever happening in nature.  

: Given enough time it does. That is the thing with chance, it may happen a million years from now, or it may happen tomorrow. Some can't handle the concept of a random universe so they create a creator.

: : I also do not know of any evidence of an observable mutation that ever resulted in a superior creature.  I realize that we have dominant and recessive genes that allow us to adapt to our surroundings, resulting in changes in color, etc., but in order for a new species to evolve from an old one, there must be mutation.

: That is one of the misconceptions about evolution, that it HAS to go from inferior to superior. This is not necessarily true. Evolution is what helps an organism survive long enough to reproduce, it doesn't have to lead to a superior form of life such as us humans.

: If we were to start from scratch life on this planet would be completely in form.

: : Haven't the processes always been the same, or did nature do a 180 at some point?  If in the distant past, order ascended from chaos, and mutation was once a good thing, then everything is working in  reverse now.     

: How so? The universe isn't as all &quot;ordered&quot; as we would like to believe it is. We are only aware of a very tiny percentage of it.

: One example of a mutation that I can remember is about a moth in England when they were burning a lot of coal. The moth was the same color as a tree, but with all of the soot covering the trees they can't hide from their predators. There was a mutant form that would appear every now and then that was black which matched up with the sooted trees. Not the &quot;normal&quot; moths were getting eatened by their predators which allowed the mutant moths to survive and reproduce more than the others. Though, now that they are not burning as much coal in England as they once did things have reversed with the moths. Evolution in action.

