    <center>
      <h1>Re: P.S.</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:lgrant@netonecom.net">Lynn</a> on December 19, 1996 at 18:05:52:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="555.html">Re: P.S.</a> posted by Stephen Charchuk on December 19, 1996 at 15:15:24:<p>
<br>: <br>: : Not so fast!<br>: : Evolution:  the DOCTRINE that all forms of life originated by descent, with gradual or abrupt modifications, from preexisting forms which themselves trace backward in a continuing series to the most rudimentary organisms.<p>: Doctrine applies to religion and politics, not science. <p>These are the definitions I got from Webster's dictionary.<p>: : Big Bang:  astronomical THEORY that the universe began in a single, gigantic explosion of flammable gases<p>: Theory: 2. A formulation of underlying principles of certain observed phenomena which has been verified to some degree.<p>As I stated above, I realize the DOCTRINE of evolution, and the Big Bang THEORY are based in part on scientific theory and part on conjecture.  Your definition is no different than mine.<p><p>: You're thinking of a hypothesis. Many get the two mixed up.<p>I'm not mixed up at all.<p>: : As you can see, we are dealing with BELIEFS which are based both on evidence and conjecture, which, even if proven true, do not explain how these gases, from which all the universe is comprised, came into being.  Nor does it deal with the obvious problem of how the resulting solid particles, hurling through space from the explosion ordered themselves into a complex universe.  I cannot think of a single instance of this ever happening in nature.  <p>: Given enough time it does. That is the thing with chance, it may happen a million years from now, or it may happen tomorrow. Some can't handle the concept of a random universe so they create a creator.<p>Again, do you have any evidence of this, other than the THEORY of evolution?  I can "handle the concept" of a randon universe, it's just that no one has given me a good explanation for it.  Saying that, over enough time flying particles from an explosion will organize into a universe full of diverse life forms, is like saying that, over enough time, the dirt in my back yard will form itself into an adobie.<p>: : I also do not know of any evidence of an observable mutation that ever resulted in a superior creature.  I realize that we have dominant and recessive genes that allow us to adapt to our surroundings, resulting in changes in color, etc., but in order for a new species to evolve from an old one, there must be mutation.<p>: That is one of the misconceptions about evolution, that it HAS to go from inferior to superior. This is not necessarily true. Evolution is what helps an organism survive long enough to reproduce, it doesn't have to lead to a superior form of life such as us humans.<p>As I said, I realize that we have recessive genes that gradually become dominant as our surroundings change.  This still does not explain how all these thousands of mutations created new creatures from old. As far as I am aware, mutations only result in defects.  <br>Obviously , the theory of evolution requires that higher life forms evolve from lower ones, so I don't understand your point about not having to evolve into a superior form of life.  Where is the real evidence that one species ever evolved into another?  This leads back to my mutation question, which I still haven't gotten an answer to.  My mind is open, convince me.  <p>: If we were to start from scratch life on this planet would be completely in form.<p>You perplex me.  Please explain.<p>: : Haven't the processes always been the same, or did nature do a 180 at some point?  If in the distant past, order ascended from chaos, and mutation was once a good thing, then everything is working in  reverse now.     <p>: How so? The universe isn't as all "ordered" as we would like to believe it is. We are only aware of a very tiny percentage of it.<p>Again, please explain this disorder to me.  I don't get it.<p>: One example of a mutation that I can remember is about a moth in England when they were burning a lot of coal. The moth was the same color as a tree, but with all of the soot covering the trees they can't hide from their predators. There was a mutant form that would appear every now and then that was black which matched up with the sooted trees. Not the "normal" moths were getting eatened by their predators which allowed the mutant moths to survive and reproduce more than the others. Though, now that they are not burning as much coal in England as they once did things have reversed with the moths. Evolution in action.<p>This is not evolution of species, it is merely a color change.
<br>
