    <center>
      <h1>Re: P.S.</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:nosferat@auracom.com">Stephen Charchuk</a> on December 17, 1996 at 01:30:33:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="519.html">Re: P.S.</a> posted by Lynn on December 15, 1996 at 17:46:57:<p>
: I don't think it is any less reasonable to believe the universe was created, than it is to believe everything just appeared and then arranged itself into a complex universe full of complex organisms.  You have not proven your point, nor can you have any idea what discoveries, scientific or otherwise, that will be made beyond your lifetime.  Yes, time will tell, but there's no way you can know what it will say. <p>The classic question to this is who created the creator, if there is one?<p>Matter is always being created and destroyed. With time comes complexcity. We are seeing everything from this end of time, it was not always like this. Humans start as simple cells and grow into trillions of cells. We don't just appear whole and adult, it takes time. The estimated age of the universe is on the raise again after they study more objects ou there.<br>The Universe itself may be simular in structure as a living system with our solar system being just one atom in its body.<p>Certain trends have already answer many questions about the Universe already.<p>Science doesn't deal with proof, it deals with evidence. And the evidence points to a non-creator universe.<p>Even the Pope has accepted evolution as a fact now.<br>
<br>
