Posted by <a href="mailto:lgrant@netonecom.net">Lynn</a> on December 16, 1996 at 18:12:38:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="526.html">"Conservative Bank" uses graphology in hiring...</a> posted by Lori Bowden on December 16, 1996 at 14:02:48:<p>
<br>: So I'm reading my paper over a nice cup of coffee<br>: this morning (Santa Rosa Press Democrat for Monday December 16, 1996)<br>: and the front page article on the *Business* page is:<br>: "Making the write (sic) choice - Exchange Bank uses graphology<br>: in recuiting". I CANT BELIEVE THIS! I blink hoping that it<br>: is just a typo, but no, it is an article (taking up almost<br>: 2 *whole* newspaper pages) on how this "conservative <br>: 106-year old" bank "and a growing number of companies<br>: across the country are using newly sophisticated handwriting<br>: studies in their personnel decisions." I won't go on about<br>: this because the article speaks for itself. If you are interested,<br>: the article is on the web at: www.pressdemo.com/news/12-16/st004.html<br>: If you want to call the bank to comment (I did), the name of the woman<br>: at the bank is Sharon Stockham (she is quoted in the article) - <br>: the number there is: (707) 524-3222.<p>: Lori Bowden<br>: Santa Rosa CA<p><br>Dear Lori,<p>I am equally outraged, but not suprised.  Your employer may also access your medical records and credit history, give you a psychological exam and/or polygraph test, deny employment to you if you smoke, award bonus's according to how thin you are (it's true...a friend of mine works at a place that gives bonus's based on your height/weight ratio), pee in a cup...well, I could go on forever.  It sound's to me like the handwriting thing might be a way of not hiring someone without telling them the real reason why.<p>I really have no hope that the trend will change.  <p>By the way, just for fun, a lady came to the radio station where I work and did a handwriting analysis of all the disc jockeys.  It's really amazing how accurate she was.  It's a good thing they didn't use this kind of analysis in hiring me.  She said I was so sensitive that I could almost feel what people are thinking.  This is not necessarily a good thing. 
<br>
