Posted by <a href="mailto:bdog@sonic.net">Lori Bowden</a> on December 16, 1996 at 14:02:48:<p>
So I'm reading my paper over a nice cup of coffee<br>this morning (Santa Rosa Press Democrat for Monday December 16, 1996)<br>and the front page article on the *Business* page is:<br>"Making the write (sic) choice - Exchange Bank uses graphology<br>in recuiting". I CANT BELIEVE THIS! I blink hoping that it<br>is just a typo, but no, it is an article (taking up almost<br>2 *whole* newspaper pages) on how this "conservative <br>106-year old" bank "and a growing number of companies<br>across the country are using newly sophisticated handwriting<br>studies in their personnel decisions." I won't go on about<br>this because the article speaks for itself. If you are interested,<br>the article is on the web at: www.pressdemo.com/news/12-16/st004.html<br>If you want to call the bank to comment (I did), the name of the woman<br>at the bank is Sharon Stockham (she is quoted in the article) - <br>the number there is: (707) 524-3222.<p>Lori Bowden<br>Santa Rosa CA<p>
