Posted by <a href="mailto:philippa@webtv.net">Philippa</a> on December 18, 1996 at 00:14:51:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="526.html">"Conservative Bank" uses graphology in hiring...</a> posted by Lori Bowden on December 16, 1996 at 14:02:48:<p>
 <br>: So I'm reading my paper over a nice cup of coffee <br>: this morning (Santa Rosa Press Democrat for Monday <br>December 16, 1996) <br>: and the front page article on the *Business* page <br>is: <br>: "Making the write (sic) choice - Exchange Bank uses <br>graphology <br>: in recuiting". I CANT BELIEVE THIS! I blink hoping <br>that it <br>: is just a typo, but no, it is an article (taking up <br>almost <br>: 2 *whole* newspaper pages) on how this <br>"conservative <br>: 106-year old" bank "and a growing number of <br>companies <br>: across the country are using newly sophisticated <br>handwriting <br>: studies in their personnel decisions." I won't go <br>on about <br>: this because the article speaks for itself. If you <br>are interested, <br>: the article is on the web at: <br>www.pressdemo.com/news/12-16/st004.html <br>: If you want to call the bank to comment (I did), <br>the name of the woman <br>: at the bank is Sharon Stockham (she is quoted in <br>the article) - <br>: the number there is: (707) 524-3222. <br> <br>: Lori Bowden <br>: Santa Rosa CA <br> <br>Interest in handwriting as an expression of <br>personality is really as old as the use of writing <br>itself.  The school of fixed signs, which emphasize <br>the elements of handwritung - such as the forms of t <br>bars, i dots, hooks, & flourishes, has been abandoned <br>by modern graphoanalysists with the emphasis now on <br>overall aspects. Handwriting must be perveived as a <br>whole and be considered as one piece of the puzzle in <br>a psychological profile.  The "danger" involved in <br>amateur handwriting analysis is that sweeping <br>generalizations based on oversimplifications could <br>lead to discrimination.
<br>
