Posted by <a href="mailto:philippa@webtv.net">PHILIPPA</a> on December 22, 1996 at 15:12:59:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="550.html">Re: "Conservative Bank" uses graphology in hiring...</a> posted by Lori Bowden on December 18, 1996 at 17:49:01:<p>
 <br>: : itself.  The school of fixed signs, which <br>emphasize <br>: : the elements of handwritung - such as the forms <br>of t <br>: : bars, i dots, hooks, & flourishes, has been <br>abandoned <br>: : by modern graphoanalysists with the emphasis now <br>on <br>: : overall aspects. Handwriting must be perveived as <br>a <br>: : whole and be considered as one piece of the <br>puzzle in <br>: : a psychological profile.  The "danger" involved <br>in <br> <br>: Hmmmm it appears to me that you are saying that the <p>: modern graphoanalysists are using methods that have <br>been <br>: scientifically validated. Can you point me to some <br>studies <br>: on this so I can read up on it? <br> <br>: The attached link points to the Skeptics Dictionary <br>entry <br>: on graphology. (not that I would rely on that alone <br>but it <br>: was handy) <br> <br>: Lori <br> <br>A search of the net did in fact confirm that there <br>are a lot of self taught "experts" out there making <br>dubious claims about gaphology.  I do believe, <br>however that there are qualified experts with a <br>strong background in psycholgy and/or forensic <br>pychology.  An email to Sheila Lowe at <br>WrtExpert@aol.com resulted in a reply that claimed <br>graphoanalysis is used by the CIA and is used by 70 <br>police departmentsin Arkansas who recieve training in <br>recognizing Menacing Behavior in handwriting.  She <br>also provided me with alist of over 40n resources <br>including Journal articles and disertations related <br>to the scientific application of handwriting <br>examination in various medical and neurolgical <br>disorders.  The list of resources is too long to <br>include, but I'm sure she would forward the same <br>information to you, if requested.  Resources do <br>include the Journal of Applied Psychology, Criminal <br>Psychopathology, Mount Sinai Journal of Medicine, <br>Scientific American, and Perceptual & Motor Skills. I <br>was Not able to locate these articles online.  I have <br>also sent an email to an academic forensic <br>psycholgist asking his opinion on the scientifc <br>validation of graphoanalysis and will post his <br>response, either pro or con.   Now that I have <br>defended the use of handwriting analysis in certain <br>situations bt qualified practitioners, I weould like <br>to say that even valid science (especially social <br>science) can certainly be misapplied.  Testing of any <br>sort that does not directly relate to skills <br>requiredby a job should not be used.  Thankyou for <br>giving me the incentive to more thoroughly examine my <br>ownopinion regardingthis intriguing topic.  My <br>conclusion is that although there are legitimate uses <br>of this technique, by and large one should be wary of <br>undertrained practitioners making sweeping general <br>claims based on handwriting only and ignoring other <br>factors.  Using graphoanalysis as a screening tool is <br>probably on shaky legal ground as it could be used in <br>a discriminatory manner unrelated to actual job <br>performance requirements.    philippa
