: A search of the net did in fact confirm that there 
: are a lot of self taught &quot;experts&quot; out there making 
: dubious claims about gaphology.  I do believe, 
: however that there are qualified experts with a 
: strong background in psycholgy and/or forensic 
: pychology.  An email to Sheila Lowe at 
: WrtExpert@aol.com resulted in a reply that claimed 
: graphoanalysis is used by the CIA and is used by 70 
: police departmentsin Arkansas who recieve training in 
: recognizing Menacing Behavior in handwriting.  She 
: also provided me with alist of over 40n resources 
: including Journal articles and disertations related 
: to the scientific application of handwriting 
: examination in various medical and neurolgical 
: disorders.  The list of resources is too long to 
: include, but I'm sure she would forward the same 
: information to you, if requested.  Resources do 
: include the Journal of Applied Psychology, Criminal 
: Psychopathology, Mount Sinai Journal of Medicine, 
: Scientific American, and Perceptual & Motor Skills. I 
: was Not able to locate these articles online.  I have 
: also sent an email to an academic forensic 
: psycholgist asking his opinion on the scientifc 
: validation of graphoanalysis and will post his 
: response, either pro or con.   Now that I have 
: defended the use of handwriting analysis in certain 
: situations bt qualified practitioners, I weould like 
: to say that even valid science (especially social 
: science) can certainly be misapplied.  Testing of any 
: sort that does not directly relate to skills 
: requiredby a job should not be used.  Thankyou for 
: giving me the incentive to more thoroughly examine my 
: ownopinion regardingthis intriguing topic.  My 
: conclusion is that although there are legitimate uses 
: of this technique, by and large one should be wary of 
: undertrained practitioners making sweeping general 
: claims based on handwriting only and ignoring other 
: factors.  Using graphoanalysis as a screening tool is 
: probably on shaky legal ground as it could be used in 
: a discriminatory manner unrelated to actual job 
: performance requirements.    philippa

