    <center>
      <h1>Re: understanding skepticism/agnosticism</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Amanda on December 19, 1996 at 08:36:03:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="537.html">Re: understanding skepticism/agnosticism</a> posted by Lynn on December 17, 1996 at 10:27:30:<p>
<br>: <br>: : <br>: : : Hello Skeptical Friends,<p>: : : I'm really trying to understand the philosophy of the Skeptics's Society  I've looked in the dictiontionary under "agnostic", "atheist", and "skeptic", yet I haven't found a satisfactory definition.  I'm trying to determine if "skeptics" assume there is some sort of higher power, but that the truth of the matter is unknowable, therefore, unsearchable.<p>: : As a skeptic, I try not to "assume" anything. Usually when one assumes something, that something has no proof to back it up and the skeptic in me needs evidence to believe in something. I think perhaps you're using "assume" as a synonym for "believe" - I believe in a lot of things but I'm not sure that I assume things.  I'm not quite sure what you meant by "higher power" but there is little or no evidence for such a thing so as I can only speak for myself, I don't believe in one. Hope this is relevant to what it was you were asking.<p>: <br>: Dear Amanda,<p>: I wouldn't exactly substitute "assume" for "believe".  I was trying to summarize the definition of "agnostic" that I found in the dictionary.  I probably didn't do a very good job.  <br>: I am trying to understand the thinking of friends and loved ones who are agnostic/atheist.  This is a touchy topic and I prefer to discuss it with people I know will not be offended by my curiosity.<br>: When I have attempted to get them to explain their way of thinking, the answers I get sound more like anger than disbelief.  My brother seems to be an atheist because he is disappointed in the so-called christians in the judgemental little backwoods town he lives in.  He's had a hard life and feels that they judge him.  I wouldn't be suprised if they do.  There are plenty of "christians"  out there that I'm not particularly fond of.   Others, who are agnostic, simply say they don't know if there is a God and quite frankly don't care to ponder the subject.  The agnostics puzzle me most.  If someone thinks for a second there MIGHT be a God, how could he or she not want to  know?  Since they have not taken the leap to "atheist", it seems there must be a nagging suspicion.  Are they on the fence for fear of making a decision?  <p>Hey Lynn!  If you're looking for a good set of definitions for the terms agnostic and atheist I would recommend checking out Bertrand Russell. Most agnostics make the claim they do "they don't believe that either way in God's existence" because it's a logical stand. We cannot EVER prove that God does not exist so an atheist that defines his stand on the issue as "one who claims God does not exist" is going to be shot down in a matter of seconds by anyone that knows how to use logical arguments. I'm an atheist but I define it as "one who doesn't believe in God" so by using the word "believe" I escape all possible logic arguments. Logic is a mind boggling thing and both theists and atheists use it do combat the opponent. I don't claim to be agnostic because there is evidence out there that could be used to show that it's unlikely that god exists so I'm right now holding on to the belief that he doesn't. If there were to appear evidence for the opposite claim I might change my belief system but I see this as     being rather unlikely. My dad, funny guy that he is, claims to be an agnostic because he wouldn't want to die and find himself infront of St. Peter and the pearly gates saying "SHIT!" - this way he covers his ass. Amanda
