    <center>
      <h1>Re: understanding skepticism/agnosticism</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Lynn on December 17, 1996 at 10:27:30:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="534.html">Re: understanding skepticism/agnosticism</a> posted by Amanda on December 17, 1996 at 01:37:02:<p>
<br>: <br>: : Hello Skeptical Friends,<p>: : I'm really trying to understand the philosophy of the Skeptics's Society  I've looked in the dictiontionary under "agnostic", "atheist", and "skeptic", yet I haven't found a satisfactory definition.  I'm trying to determine if "skeptics" assume there is some sort of higher power, but that the truth of the matter is unknowable, therefore, unsearchable.<p>: As a skeptic, I try not to "assume" anything. Usually when one assumes something, that something has no proof to back it up and the skeptic in me needs evidence to believe in something. I think perhaps you're using "assume" as a synonym for "believe" - I believe in a lot of things but I'm not sure that I assume things.  I'm not quite sure what you meant by "higher power" but there is little or no evidence for such a thing so as I can only speak for myself, I don't believe in one. Hope this is relevant to what it was you were asking.<p><br>Dear Amanda,<p>I wouldn't exactly substitute "assume" for "believe".  I was trying to summarize the definition of "agnostic" that I found in the dictionary.  I probably didn't do a very good job.  <br>I am trying to understand the thinking of friends and loved ones who are agnostic/atheist.  This is a touchy topic and I prefer to discuss it with people I know will not be offended by my curiosity.<br>When I have attempted to get them to explain their way of thinking, the answers I get sound more like anger than disbelief.  My brother seems to be an atheist because he is disappointed in the so-called christians in the judgemental little backwoods town he lives in.  He's had a hard life and feels that they judge him.  I wouldn't be suprised if they do.  There are plenty of "christians"  out there that I'm not particularly fond of.   Others, who are agnostic, simply say they don't know if there is a God and quite frankly don't care to ponder the subject.  The agnostics puzzle me most.  If someone thinks for a second there MIGHT be a God, how could he or she not want to  know?  Since they have not taken the leap to "atheist", it seems there must be a nagging suspicion.  Are they on the fence for fear of making a decision?  
<br>
