    <center>
      <h1>Re: understanding skepticism/agnosticism</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:kakadoo@sprynet.com">Amanda</a> on December 17, 1996 at 01:37:02:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="515.html">understanding skepticism/agnosticism</a> posted by Lynn on December 14, 1996 at 17:04:38:<p>
<br>: Hello Skeptical Friends,<p>: I'm really trying to understand the philosophy of the Skeptics's Society  I've looked in the dictiontionary under "agnostic", "atheist", and "skeptic", yet I haven't found a satisfactory definition.  I'm trying to determine if "skeptics" assume there is some sort of higher power, but that the truth of the matter is unknowable, therefore, unsearchable.<p>As a skeptic, I try not to "assume" anything. Usually when one assumes something, that something has no proof to back it up and the skeptic in me needs evidence to believe in something. I think perhaps you're using "assume" as a synonym for "believe" - I believe in a lot of things but I'm not sure that I assume things.  I'm not quite sure what you meant by "higher power" but there is little or no evidence for such a thing so as I can only speak for myself, I don't believe in one. Hope this is relevant to what it was you were asking.
<br>
