<a name="postfp">Post a Followup</a><p>
<form method=POST action="http://www.skeptic.com/cgi-local/skepticboard.pl">
<input type=hidden name="followup" value="515,534,537,546">
<input type=hidden name="origname" value="David">
<input type=hidden name="origsubject" value="Re: understanding skepticism/agnosticism">
<input type=hidden name="origdate" value="December 18, 1996 at 12:29:54">
Name: <input type=text name="name" size=50><br>
E-Mail: <input type=text name="email" size=50><p>
Subject: <input type=text name="subject"value="Re: understanding skepticism/agnosticism" size=50><p>
Comments:<br>
<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: : 
: : : 
: : : : Hello Skeptical Friends,

: : : : I'm really trying to understand the philosophy of the Skeptics's Society  I've looked in the dictiontionary under &quot;agnostic&quot;, &quot;atheist&quot;, and &quot;skeptic&quot;, yet I haven't found a satisfactory definition.  I'm trying to determine if &quot;skeptics&quot; assume there is some sort of higher power, but that the truth of the matter is unknowable, therefore, unsearchable.

: : : As a skeptic, I try not to &quot;assume&quot; anything. Usually when one assumes something, that something has no proof to back it up and the skeptic in me needs evidence to believe in something. I think perhaps you're using &quot;assume&quot; as a synonym for &quot;believe&quot; - I believe in a lot of things but I'm not sure that I assume things.  I'm not quite sure what you meant by &quot;higher power&quot; but there is little or no evidence for such a thing so as I can only speak for myself, I don't believe in one. Hope this is relevant to what it was you were asking.

: : 
: : Dear Amanda,

: : I wouldn't exactly substitute &quot;assume&quot; for &quot;believe&quot;.  I was trying to summarize the definition of &quot;agnostic&quot; that I found in the dictionary.  I probably didn't do a very good job.  
: : I am trying to understand the thinking of friends and loved ones who are agnostic/atheist.  This is a touchy topic and I prefer to discuss it with people I know will not be offended by my curiosity.
: : When I have attempted to get them to explain their way of thinking, the answers I get sound more like anger than disbelief.  My brother seems to be an atheist because he is disappointed in the so-called christians in the judgemental little backwoods town he lives in.  He's had a hard life and feels that they judge him.  I wouldn't be suprised if they do.  There are plenty of &quot;christians&quot;  out there that I'm not particularly fond of.   Others, who are agnostic, simply say they don't know if there is a God and quite frankly don't care to ponder the subject.  The agnostics puzzle me most.  If someone thinks for a second there MIGHT be a God, how could he or she not want to  know?  Since they have not taken the leap to &quot;atheist&quot;, it seems there must be a nagging suspicion.  Are they on the fence for fear of making a decision?  

: Lynn,

: It isn't about fear of making a decision, it's about saying that there isn't enough evidence to make a decision.  Most agnostics would say that most evidence points to there being no God but that it is not conclusive.  In fact it is almost impossible to find conclusive evidence to the contrary of the existence of anything (UFOs, ghosts, bigfoot, fairies etc. etc. - which IMHO are at least as likely as a God, but I'm agnostic about them too).

</textarea>
