br>: : survive in the ark. For these, and other reasons (ex. geological <br>: : evidence lacking, etc.) I find that the story of the flood has to be<br>: : viewed as non-literal.<p>: : On to the New Testament. I personally know people who could write <br>: : something like it.  They are sincere, they believe, and they want<br>: : to help the cause. With wishful thinking they convince themselves of<br>: : all kinds of miracles or "interventions" by God (answers to prayer) <br>: : of some kind or another. Eyewitness accounts written and recorded<br>: : 70 to 120 years after the fact by a second or third party could<br>: : contain some of the same "wishful thinking". Is it possible to be a <br>: : part of something that is "in part" a piece of wishful thinking, and <br>: : then be willing to die for it?  Yes, there seems to be ample evidence<br>: : of that around in the Jonestowns, the Koreshes, etc.<p>: : These are some of the things that put me into the agnostic camp. I <br>: : cannot say there is "not" a god out there somewhere. I am quite <br>: : convinced that if there is, that she/he is not the god that I grew up<br>: : believing in as an evangelical christian.<p>: <br>: You bring up some valid points.  These are areas I hope to have a better understanding of someday.  Hopefully I will be able to respond soon.<p><p>Hi, I'm back, Bob.<p>First, I want to thank you and everyone at this message board for your gracious hospitality.  This has been a great learning experience for me.  Not only do I have a better understanding of skeptics/agnostics/atheists, but your last posting sent me on a search for evidence of my own beliefs that has left me feeling great!<br>I've decided not to try and convince you any longer.  If I do, I'm going to start sounding like a preacher.  I can sight scientists and experts who say one thing.  You can sight those who have a differing opinion. The argument is ultimately spiritual and, unless you tell me otherwise, I assume that's not somewhere you want to go.  Having said that, let me tell you one thing that I am so excited about that I've got to share it.<p>I'm having the greatest Christmas ever!  I am experiencing some of those "percieved" miracles.  As I stated in my original posting, I am here out of concern for my loved ones.  If you knew them, you would KNOW that it's a miracle that my mom, dad, and brother <br>are now praying and reading the Bible.  I only found out yesterday!<br>Their experience seems to be taking shape much the way mine did.   I am so thrilled that even though we are living a thousand miles apart here on earth, that we'll be together in perfect love in the paradise <br>of God, forever.   Yipeeeeeeeeee!!
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
