Comments:<br>
<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: 
: : : : 
: : : : : : 
: : : : : : : 
: : : : : : : : Hello Skeptical Friends,

: : : : : : : : I'm really trying to understand the philosophy of the Skeptics's Society  I've looked in the dictiontionary under &quot;agnostic&quot;, &quot;atheist&quot;, and &quot;skeptic&quot;, yet I haven't found a satisfactory definition.  I'm trying to determine if &quot;skeptics&quot; assume there is some sort of higher power, but that the truth of the matter is unknowable, therefore, unsearchable.

: : : : : : : As a skeptic, I try not to &quot;assume&quot; anything. Usually when one assumes something, that something has no proof to back it up and the skeptic in me needs evidence to believe in something. I think perhaps you're using &quot;assume&quot; as a synonym for &quot;believe&quot; - I believe in a lot of things but I'm not sure that I assume things.  I'm not quite sure what you meant by &quot;higher power&quot; but there is little or no evidence for such a thing so as I can only speak for myself, I don't believe in one. Hope this is relevant to what it was you were asking.

: : : : : : 
: : : : : : Dear Amanda,

: : : : : : I wouldn't exactly substitute &quot;assume&quot; for &quot;believe&quot;.  I was trying to summarize the definition of &quot;agnostic&quot; that I found in the dictionary.  I probably didn't do a very good job.  
: : : : : : I am trying to understand the thinking of friends and loved ones who are agnostic/atheist.  This is a touchy topic and I prefer to discuss it with people I know will not be offended by my curiosity.
: : : : : : When I have attempted to get them to explain their way of thinking, the answers I get sound more like anger than disbelief.  My brother seems to be an atheist because he is disappointed in the so-called christians in the judgemental little backwoods town he lives in.  He's had a hard life and feels that they judge him.  I wouldn't be suprised if they do.  There are plenty of &quot;christians&quot;  out there that I'm not particularly fond of.   Others, who are agnostic, simply say they don't know if there is a God and quite frankly don't care to ponder the subject.  The agnostics puzzle me most.  If someone thinks for a second there MIGHT be a God, how could he or she not want to  know?  Since they have not taken the leap to &quot;atheist&quot;, it seems there must be a nagging suspicion.  Are they on the fence for fear of making a decision?  

: : : : : Lynn,

: : : : : It isn't about fear of making a decision, it's about saying that there isn't enough evidence to make a decision.  Most agnostics would say that most evidence points to there being no God but that it is not conclusive.  In fact it is almost impossible to find conclusive evidence to the contrary of the existence of anything (UFOs, ghosts, bigfoot, fairies etc. etc. - which IMHO are at least as likely as a God, but I'm agnostic about them too).

: : : : Hi David,

: : : : Thank you for responding.

: : : : I would be interested in your opinion about all the eyewitness accounts of God and his dealings with mankind that are recorded in the Bible.   

: : : Lynn

: : : My opinion on eyewitness accounts goes like this. It starts in the
: : : Old Testament. To me, the evidence of antiquity of the earth is beyond
: : : reasonable doubt. The account of creation cannot be taken literally.

: : : There are a number of Old Testament accounts that are impossible. 
: : : For example, the ark. 
: : : There is simply no possible way that all the species that exist could
: : : fit, survive, or anything in a vessel that size. So, the apologists,
: : : such as Gish et al propose &quot;kinds&quot; rather that species, and suggest
: : : some limited &quot;evolution&quot; from kind to species. This also was a recent
: : : as 3000 years ago, if you use a literal approach and accept Usher's 
: : : chronology. Whether 3000 or 8000 years (the maximum suggested by the 
: : : creation science people the last I heard) you would still have to 
: : : accept an extremely rapid rate of evolution to develop all the species
: : : existing today from the number of &quot;kinds&quot; that could fit in and 
: : : survive in the ark. For these, and other reasons (ex. geological 
: : : evidence lacking, etc.) I find that the story of the flood has to be
: : : viewed as non-literal.

: : : On to the New Testament. I personally know people who could write 
: : : something like it.  They are sincere, they believe, and they want
: : : to help the cause. With wishful thinking they convince themselves of
: : : all kinds of miracles or &quot;interventions&quot; by God (answers to prayer) 
: : : of some kind or another. Eyewitness accounts written and recorded
: : : 70 to 120 years after the fact by a second or third party could
: : : contain some of the same &quot;wishful thinking&quot;. Is it possible to be a 
: : : part of something that is &quot;in part&quot; a piece of wishful thinking, and 
: : : then be willing to die for it?  Yes, there seems to be ample evidence
: : : of that around in the Jonestowns, the Koreshes, etc.

: : : These are some of the things that put me into the agnostic camp. I 
: : : cannot say there is &quot;not&quot; a god out there somewhere. I am quite 
: : : convinced that if there is, that she/he is not the god that I grew up
: : : believing in as an evangelical christian.

: : 
: : You bring up some valid points.  These are areas I hope to have a better understanding of someday.  Hopefully I will be able to respond soon.


: Hi, I'm back, Bob.

: First, I want to thank you and everyone at this message board for your gracious hospitality.  This has been a great learning experience for me.  Not only do I have a better understanding of skeptics/agnostics/atheists, but your last posting sent me on a search for evidence of my own beliefs that has left me feeling great!
: I've decided not to try and convince you any longer.  If I do, I'm going to start sounding like a preacher.  I can sight scientists and experts who say one thing.  You can sight those who have a differing opinion. The argument is ultimately spiritual and, unless you tell me otherwise, I assume that's not somewhere you want to go.  Having said that, let me tell you one thing that I am so excited about that I've got to share it.

: I'm having the greatest Christmas ever!  I am experiencing some of those &quot;percieved&quot; miracles.  As I stated in my original posting, I am here out of concern for my loved ones.  If you knew them, you would KNOW that it's a miracle that my mom, dad, and brother 
: are now praying and reading the Bible.  I only found out yesterday!
: Their experience seems to be taking shape much the way mine did.   I am so thrilled that even though we are living a thousand miles apart here on earth, that we'll be together in perfect love in the paradise 
: of God, forever.   Yipeeeeeeeeee!!

</textarea>
