    <center>
      <h1>Re: GOD...defined</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Amanda on January 05, 1997 at 09:18:53:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="834.html">Re: GOD...defined</a> posted by grasshopper on January 04, 1997 at 19:13:58:<p>
<br>: <br>: : Well, put 'em out on the table then - I'll try to give you some evidence for the unlikeliness. This is how we progress - we make claims, back 'em up with evidence, weigh the evidence pro and con, and believe or disbelieve. So, let's play!<p>: Ok, I'll try to make up different theories of 'god', so here are a few.<br>: Maybe, god creates the universe, arranging the planets...to the minute<br>: detail (making it perpetually expand and all)...this god has no intrest <br>: in us now...<p>This just sounds like a term being used for the indifferent laws of the Universe - some of which we've discovered. Also, there is some evidence for the Big Bang Theory resulting in the arrangemeent of the galaxies, solar systems, suns and planets - it has more weight than the idea that a guy in th sky was playing with balls and stuff so the belief should sway in the former's direction.<br>If you're just using the word "god" to define what we know thus far regarding how the planets came to be - this is a bad word to use - supernaturalism is implied when using the word god.<p>: hmm...this is all a hologram...I would concider the maker of the hologram<br>: to be 'god' (all definitions)...a very detailed holagram.<p>Some psychologists have hypothesized that idea - that this is all a dream but hell, we've got to put a bit of stock in what we sense - We start by realizing that there is more to reality then what goes on in our mind - we use our senses to observe our surroundings and there are certain facts we can discover - we are real and we exist. A God making this all for us is probably the best idea out there but still, no evidence and therefore no belief.<p>: I made this world (universe we perseve)...just yesterday...to the finest detail<br>: your memories and all.<p>Ok, let's see you do it all again. Evidence - none.<p>:  There are a few...of course there are many more...I would enjoy arguing these<br>: out and I'll make up some more possiblities later.<p>The point is you have to back up your claims with evidence and you're not doing that whereas we have evidence for an explanation to this entire universe where a god is not necessary. What belief would you think would help us survive in the cosmos?<br>You do have a great imagination though, write some scifi books!
<br>
