<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: GOD...defined</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: GOD...defined</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Tyler Bradley on January 10, 1997 at 15:19:37:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="1014.html">Re: GOD...defined</a> posted by Stephen Charchuk on January 10, 1997 at 11:03:12:<p>
: : Yes, but isn't the issue about why this way and not one of the other possibilities?<p>: Again, why not?<p>That is exactly my point, thanks.  Science and rationalism will not answer this large question b/c we are reduced to just throwing up our arms and saying, "Why not?".  We dance around in the semantic game, but there is no answer through evidence.  Philosophical and theological treatments are what's left.  I put my coins into the philosopher's hat first though.<br>==================================<p>: : I do not believe that I've ever made an argument for a human preferred place.<p>: You do just that when you try to give a meaning to it.<p>No, I do not think so.  Think of the many things that I assume you give meaning to in your life; work, family, thought, etc.  In the cosmological sense, these things are pitifully insignificant.  Your objection appears to be a theological one, and I state nothing about either that, or a God's love for humanity. <br>=================================<p>: : This will only address replication, not sentience.  Sentience is such a transcendent term, not to mention very unclear, that this research likely will not reveal any clues.<p>: Sentience occures when a neural-net reaches a certain level of complexity. There is much progress happening now in the area of AI.<p>Tell me where that line is?  Are you defining it?  Is someone else?  Can you be sure it is a universal truth?   =================================<p><br>: : Are you sure?  Neuro-nets are good for an electrochemical transmission of information but alas, pathways can be altered from any number of unpredictable events, perceptions and feelings.  So much so that I cannot concur...<p>: How many times have great discoveries been made when something totally unexpected had happened? All our minds are are very complex neural-nets. I've even hear it called our metaprogram.<p>I'm not sure of your argument here, but I agree that we have "programming" from DNA to algorithmic thought processes- but that is where it ends.
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
<a name="followups">Follow Ups:</a><br>
<ul><!--insert: 1026-->
<!--top: 1042--><li><a href="1042.html">Re: GOD...defined</a> <b>Stephen Charchuk</b> <i>23:29:42 1/10/97</i>
(<!--responses: 1042-->0)
