<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
<a name="postfp">Post a Followup</a><p>
<form method=POST action="http://www.skeptic.com/cgi-local/skepticboard.pl">
<input type=hidden name="followup" value="792,794,795,806,820,827,834,860,874,885,957,967,973,977,1002,1014,1026">
<input type=hidden name="origname" value="Tyler Bradley">
<input type=hidden name="origsubject" value="Re: GOD...defined">
<input type=hidden name="origdate" value="January 10, 1997 at 15:19:37">
Name: <input type=text name="name" size=50><br>
E-Mail: <input type=text name="email" size=50><p>
Subject: <input type=text name="subject"value="Re: GOD...defined" size=50><p>
Comments:<br>
<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: : : Yes, but isn't the issue about why this way and not one of the other possibilities?

: : Again, why not?

: That is exactly my point, thanks.  Science and rationalism will not answer this large question b/c we are reduced to just throwing up our arms and saying, &quot;Why not?&quot;.  We dance around in the semantic game, but there is no answer through evidence.  Philosophical and theological treatments are what's left.  I put my coins into the philosopher's hat first though.
: ==================================

: : : I do not believe that I've ever made an argument for a human preferred place.

: : You do just that when you try to give a meaning to it.

: No, I do not think so.  Think of the many things that I assume you give meaning to in your life; work, family, thought, etc.  In the cosmological sense, these things are pitifully insignificant.  Your objection appears to be a theological one, and I state nothing about either that, or a God's love for humanity. 
: =================================

: : : This will only address replication, not sentience.  Sentience is such a transcendent term, not to mention very unclear, that this research likely will not reveal any clues.

: : Sentience occures when a neural-net reaches a certain level of complexity. There is much progress happening now in the area of AI.

: Tell me where that line is?  Are you defining it?  Is someone else?  Can you be sure it is a universal truth?   =================================

: 
: : : Are you sure?  Neuro-nets are good for an electrochemical transmission of information but alas, pathways can be altered from any number of unpredictable events, perceptions and feelings.  So much so that I cannot concur...

: : How many times have great discoveries been made when something totally unexpected had happened? All our minds are are very complex neural-nets. I've even hear it called our metaprogram.

: I'm not sure of your argument here, but I agree that we have &quot;programming&quot; from DNA to algorithmic thought processes- but that is where it ends.

</textarea>
