  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: GOD...defined</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:nosferat@auracom.com">Stephen Charchuk</a> on January 10, 1997 at 23:29:42:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="1026.html">Re: GOD...defined</a> posted by Tyler Bradley on January 10, 1997 at 15:19:37:<p>
: That is exactly my point, thanks.  Science and rationalism will not answer this large question b/c we are reduced to just throwing up our arms and saying, "Why not?".  We dance around in the semantic game, but there is no answer through evidence.  Philosophical and theological treatments are what's left.  I put my coins into the philosopher's hat first though.<p><br>One can't answer the unanswerable. To do so can only be opinion and conjecture set to help us handle reality. We are only fooling ourselves if we think that we could get the answer that easily.<p>: No, I do not think so.  Think of the many things that I assume you give meaning to in your life; work, family, thought, etc.  In the cosmological sense, these things are pitifully insignificant.  Your objection appears to be a theological one, and I state nothing about either that, or a God's love for humanity. <p><br>We try to give meaning to something that is far beyond our own limited standards and perceptions.<p>: Tell me where that line is?  Are you defining it?  Is someone else?  Can you be sure it is a universal truth?   <p>When does a baby go from acting merely on instinct to be a sentient being?<p>: I'm not sure of your argument here, but I agree that we have "programming" from DNA to algorithmic thought processes- but that is where it ends.<p><br>Are YOU so sure of this yourself? Will one day the Internet become a sentient being when enough systems go online? Have you read "The Moon is a Harsh Misteress" by Robert A. Heinlein? It is mainly about a computer that attains sentience after it system has a certain about of processing power. Maybe we are the sum of our parts? BTW, I here that they are going to make a movie of this book soon.<br>
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
