  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Free will and its contradiction in religion.</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:nosferat@auracom.com">Stephen Charchuk</a> on January 10, 1997 at 22:47:03:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="1022.html">Re: Free will and its contradiction in religion.</a> posted by Lynn on January 10, 1997 at 12:10:27:<p>
: This is NOT the central issue of the question.  My point is, you can do anything you please, just don't expect that there won't be consequences.  The topic was religious hypocricy, therefore it can only be debated in religious terms, unless of course the question is rhetorical and an opposite point of view is unwelcome.   <p>The question wasn't about hypocrisy, religious or otherwise. It is about the contradictions in religion's view of the concept of free will. And an opposite view is always welcome, that is why I had posted the question in the first place. Hypocrisy is saying that one doesn't steal, but will steal anyways<p>Of course they are consequences to our actions, but they may not be that ones which you belief they are. A person murders another, if they get caught they either go to prison or are executed. It's not a perfect system, but it does work. We make our choices and in most cases it is of our own free will, not some influence by either a good, or an evil enity. It is US alone.<p>
<br>
