  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Carl Sagan</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Tyler on December 31, 1996 at 02:50:29:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="661.html">Carl Sagan</a> posted by Amanda on December 30, 1996 at 18:30:38:<p>
: When I subscribed to "Skeptic" magazine over the holidays - the woman who took the call mentioned that they were working on a tribute issue on Carl Sagan much like their first issue on Asimov. It will no doubt be a beauty so I thought I'd share the info. He was a great man and I was looking at other great minds that have died such as Asimov and Russell and a host of others and I'm wondering if anyone has any examples of ones that are alive today - fighting to get science out to the people and perhaps minimizing the effects of religion and mysticism in the process? One I can think of is Stephen J. Gould. <p>Paul Davies, John Gribbin, Timothy Ferris, and Stephen Hawking (to a lesser extent) have brought difficult modern physics concepts into laymen's terms.
<br>
