<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: Being a person of faith does not mean I leave my brain behind.</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Being a person of faith does not mean I leave my brain behind.</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:skeptic@mail.get.com.tw">Carlos Javier</a> on January 06, 1997 at 22:41:19:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="613.html">Re: Being a person of faith does not mean I leave my brain behind.</a> posted by Lynn on December 28, 1996 at 18:35:25:<p>
: : <br>: : : Don't you think that the reason why most people believe in life after death is more through desire rather than fact as you state.  Nobody wants to think that when they die they are gone, nobody wants to think that great men/women or loved ones are simply dead or buried.  Unfortunately all rational evidence points to the fact that everyone is dead and gone.  However it is almost impossible to prove that anything does not exist (try and prove that fairies and goblins don't) so it ultimately comes down to your own belief system.  If you were just about any other religion other than Christian you would probably believe in reincarnation for everyone (not just Christ).<p>: : It seems like you're saying here that because we can't prove in something's non-existence then a belief in it is as reasonable as a disbelief in it but again, like the question of whether God exists or not - I'll have to disagree. There IS evidence that an afterlife is unlikely (medical science would be the leader in this I believe) so this is the criteria I use to base my beliefs on. It would seem more realistic to me that an afterlife did not exist by weighing the various findings in the matter - so I think that instead of deluding ourselves with the "pleasant" thought of a reunion with our loved ones we should find a better way for people to accept death without ripping their hearts out. It is a sad issue but I think it's even sadder that we need such an irrational belief to ease the suffering - I think there are alternatives. I apologize if I've offended anyone - feel free to offend me back!<p>: <br>: What is the harm in having the "pleasant" and comforting belief in God?  I know for a fact that I am leading a much better life than I would have without Jesus.  With help,I've learned to fight anger and hatred, bitterness and resentment, and every other negative emotion and thought with with His love which lives in me.  When someone hurts you and all you can feel is love and compassion for that person, you know it's not of yourself.  If my belief in God gives me comfort, what's the problem?  If I'm wrong, I'll never know.  If you're wrong, you've made a terrible mistake. <p><p>The point is that the evidence is so overwhelming that those of us who disbelieve christianity are NOT wrong.  If your god gave us a brain capable of logic, gave us overwhelming astronomical, archaeological, paleontological and other evidence that the universe described by the bible is one big fairy tale, and then faulted us for being infidels, he/she would be a malicious prankster unworthy of anyone's worship.  I guess I just didn't get the joke.
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
<a name="followups">Follow Ups:</a><br>
<ul><!--insert: 910-->
</ul><!--end: 910-->
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
<a name="postfp">Post a Followup</a><p>
<form method=POST action="http://www.skeptic.com/cgi-local/skepticboard.pl">
<input type=hidden name="followup" value="571,574,575,587,613,910">
<input type=hidden name="origname" value="Carlos Javier">
<input type=hidden name="origemail" value="skeptic@mail.get.com.tw">
<input type=hidden name="origsubject" value="Re: Being a person of faith does not mean I leave my brain behind.">
<input type=hidden name="origdate" value="January 06, 1997 at 22:41:19">
Name: <input type=text name="name" size=50><br>
E-Mail: <input type=text name="email" size=50><p>
Subject: <input type=text name="subject"value="Re: Being a person of faith does not mean I leave my brain behind." size=50><p>
Comments:<br>
<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: : : 
: : : : Don't you think that the reason why most people believe in life after death is more through desire rather than fact as you state.  Nobody wants to think that when they die they are gone, nobody wants to think that great men/women or loved ones are simply dead or buried.  Unfortunately all rational evidence points to the fact that everyone is dead and gone.  However it is almost impossible to prove that anything does not exist (try and prove that fairies and goblins don't) so it ultimately comes down to your own belief system.  If you were just about any other religion other than Christian you would probably believe in reincarnation for everyone (not just Christ).

: : : It seems like you're saying here that because we can't prove in something's non-existence then a belief in it is as reasonable as a disbelief in it but again, like the question of whether God exists or not - I'll have to disagree. There IS evidence that an afterlife is unlikely (medical science would be the leader in this I believe) so this is the criteria I use to base my beliefs on. It would seem more realistic to me that an afterlife did not exist by weighing the various findings in the matter - so I think that instead of deluding ourselves with the &quot;pleasant&quot; thought of a reunion with our loved ones we should find a better way for people to accept death without ripping their hearts out. It is a sad issue but I think it's even sadder that we need such an irrational belief to ease the suffering - I think there are alternatives. I apologize if I've offended anyone - feel free to offend me back!

: : 
: : What is the harm in having the &quot;pleasant&quot; and comforting belief in God?  I know for a fact that I am leading a much better life than I would have without Jesus.  With help,I've learned to fight anger and hatred, bitterness and resentment, and every other negative emotion and thought with with His love which lives in me.  When someone hurts you and all you can feel is love and compassion for that person, you know it's not of yourself.  If my belief in God gives me comfort, what's the problem?  If I'm wrong, I'll never know.  If you're wrong, you've made a terrible mistake. 


: The point is that the evidence is so overwhelming that those of us who disbelieve christianity are NOT wrong.  If your god gave us a brain capable of logic, gave us overwhelming astronomical, archaeological, paleontological and other evidence that the universe described by the bible is one big fairy tale, and then faulted us for being infidels, he/she would be a malicious prankster unworthy of anyone's worship.  I guess I just didn't get the joke.

</textarea>
<p>
