  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Being a person of faith does not mean I leave my brain behind.</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:kbaker@acadiacom.net">Jeff</a> on January 02, 1997 at 10:57:25:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="587.html">Re: Being a person of faith does not mean I leave my brain behind.</a> posted by Amanda on December 26, 1996 at 19:10:07:<p>
: <br>: : Don't you think that the reason why most people believe in life after death is more through desire rather than fact as you state.  Nobody wants to think that when they die they are gone, nobody wants to think that great men/women or loved ones are simply dead or buried.  Unfortunately all rational evidence points to the fact that everyone is dead and gone.  However it is almost impossible to prove that anything does not exist (try and prove that fairies and goblins don't) so it ultimately comes down to your own belief system.  If you were just about any other religion other than Christian you would probably believe in reincarnation for everyone (not just Christ).<p>: It seems like you're saying here that because we can't prove in something's non-existence then a belief in it is as reasonable as a disbelief in it but again, like the question of whether God exists or not - I'll have to disagree. There IS evidence that an afterlife is unlikely (medical science would be the leader in this I believe) so this is the criteria I use to base my beliefs on. It would seem more realistic to me that an afterlife did not exist by weighing the various findings in the matter - so I think that instead of deluding ourselves with the "pleasant" thought of a reunion with our loved ones we should find a better way for people to accept death without ripping their hearts out. It is a sad issue but I think it's even sadder that we need such an irrational belief to ease the suffering - I think there are alternatives. I apologize if I've offended anyone - feel free to offend me back!<p><p>I agree that the afterlife seems unlikely based on the evedence.  Just a look into brain letions point in that direction.  (Where is that part of the conscousness if the soul is the conscousness), but that is not why I don't buy into the after live idea.  It is because that afterlive cannot be proven.  To believe in an assertion without evedence is a persription to being fooled.  I read an atheist pamphlet that was a diolog between a theist and a non-theist.  <br>The non-theist say, prove that I'm not god and created you 5 min ago.  <br>The theist responed by saying he had memories past 5 min. <br>   well I put those memories there.<br>   Well, I could kill you, and that would prove it.<br>   No, I would be testing your faith.<p><br>this could go on and on, but you get the point.  An idea that cannot be tested is not worth much!<p>Jeff<br>
