Posted by <a href="mailto:kakadoo@sprynet.com">Amanda</a> on December 27, 1996 at 11:07:00:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="591.html">Re: Being a person of faith does not mean I leave my brain behind.</a> posted by Stephen Charchuk on December 26, 1996 at 23:58:34:<p>
<br>: : It seems like you're saying here that because we can't prove in something's non-existence then a belief in it is as reasonable as a disbelief in it but again, like the question of whether God exists or not - I'll have to disagree. There IS evidence that an afterlife is unlikely (medical science would be the leader in this I believe) so this is the criteria I use to base my beliefs on. It would seem more realistic to me that an afterlife did not exist by weighing the various findings in the matter - so I think that instead of deluding ourselves with the "pleasant" thought of a reunion with our loved ones we should find a better way for people to accept death without ripping their hearts out. It is a sad issue but I think it's even sadder that we need such an irrational belief to ease the suffering - I think there are alternatives. I apologize if I've offended anyone - feel free to offend me back!<p>: Even with all of the evidence for evolution and the like there will always be those who will only believe the old outdated beliefs. I'm constantly amazed that there are still people who believe that the Earth is flat and that we are the centre of the Universe.<p>: You've heard of Clarke's Law about technology and magic? Well I read in an issue of Analog that it can be applied to many in our own society today. There are people who actually think that technology is magic.<p>No, I haven't heard of Clarke's Law - tell me about it.<br>As for technology - there are already people claiming that the internet was God's creation as was the printing printing press in the Middle Ages. You can see that whenever any large advance has been made in the communications industry - a revival of religion takes place. Time magazine did a half-ass job on the subject recently. The Vatican will supposedly have a site come the new year and I imagine it will be most beautiful but the whole idea of a revival of religion scares me. We are well aware of the effects that slick advertising can have on a mind and unfortunately skeptical minds aren't the majority yet. The Celestine Prophecy also had a great deal to do with this revival I believe - in my books, spirituality and mysticism are almost synonomous with religion and it's making it very difficult for me to have a decent conversation with anyone outside of my small circle of friends and loved ones. But I digress...
