Posted by <a href="mailto:nosferat@auracom.com">Stephen Charchuk</a> on December 27, 1996 at 15:32:51:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="596.html">Re: Being a person of faith does not mean I leave my brain behind.</a> posted by Amanda on December 27, 1996 at 11:07:00:<p>
<br>: No, I haven't heard of Clarke's Law - tell me about it.<p>It is from the SF author Arthur C Clacke and goes something like this;<br>'Any suffienctly advanced technology is no different than magic to a less developed culture' This is not quite the exactly quote. Please excuse my spelling.<p>: As for technology - there are already people claiming that the internet was God's creation as was the printing printing press in the Middle Ages. You can see that whenever any large advance has been made in the communications industry - a revival of religion takes place. Time magazine did a half-ass job on the subject recently. The Vatican will supposedly have a site come the new year and I imagine it will be most beautiful but the whole idea of a revival of religion scares me. We are well aware of the effects that slick advertising can have on a mind and unfortunately skeptical minds aren't the majority yet. The Celestine Prophecy also had a great deal to do with this revival I believe - in my books, spirituality and mysticism are almost synonomous with religion and it's making it very difficult for me to have a decent conversation with anyone outside of my small circle of friends and loved ones. But I digress...<p>It really gets up my ..nose when people will give credit for all of their creativity to a god instead of takeing it from where it truly belongs, themselves. The idea of inspiration fron an outside source comes from a time when we knew almost nothing about how the brain worked and nothing at all about neuro-nets as well. Those who still use this are suffering from an inferiority complex and are trying to drag all of Mankind down with them, IMO.<br>
<br>
