Comments:<br>
<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: : Faith is a tool of fools...certainly there is no way to know anything, but
: : then deciding randomly to believe something?!  It seems people hope
: : there is an afterlife, so then they believe in it.  I would certainly
: : like a candy bar this afternoon, but I'm not going to fully believe I will
: : get one-no matter how nice it seems.
: : Instead of people finding ideas to have faith in they should deel with
: : the problem of needing something to believe-

: Grasshopper,

: You've cut right to the heart of it.  The faithful believe in something because they want to believe in it, not because there's any logical reason to do so.

: I would LOVE to believe in final justice, wouldn't you?  To know that all the rotten SOB's who've caused misery to their fellow humans have been duly punished would be great.  It would be SO satisfying to know that all those who suffer in order to stand up for goodness will be duly rewarded and fulfilled in a next life.

: That said, I DON'T believe in final justice.  How terrible, some might say.  How can he live like that?  Such people only reveal very clearly how much they are ruled by fear and insecurity.  They invent a cosmic mommy or daddy and an afterlife to sooth their worried minds.

: Checking their minds at the door is too crude an analogy.  It's better to say that they turn their minds off when illogic is more soothing than logic.

: I'll check for other postings of yours.  You seem relatively frank.

: Keep the faith. ;)

</textarea>
