<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: The particular danger of some religions (Christianity and Islam)</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: The particular danger of some religions (Christianity and Islam)</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:skeptic@mail.get.com.tw">Carlos Javier</a> on January 06, 1997 at 22:14:03:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="903.html">Re: The particular danger of some religions (Christianity and Islam)</a> posted by Jason on January 06, 1997 at 20:41:15:<p>
I'd say that we agree more than we disagree.  I do, however, take issue with the idea that I was making an ad hominem attack, as such things are repulsive to me.  Also, I would never say that atheists are communists; I might say that most communists are atheists or that the average communist is an atheist.  Give me a little credit for critical thinking, and please reread what I said about generalizations (about duly noting exceptions).<p>We both see possible danger in certain religious tendencies, but we seem to disagree as to the extent of the danger or the likelihood that it will affect us infidels.  A friend and I are in a contrasting situation on another topic; he sees conscious conspiracies in government mistreatment of minorities, where I generally give the government less credit for cunning and forethought.<p>As far as differences between Canucks and USians, don't get me started.  I grew up in Michigan.  We can start an e-mail chat about differences.  I feel they are insignificant, and are played up too much by nationalist Canadians who are tired of being mistaken for "Americans".  But such a digression should be saved for e-mail.<p>
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
<a name="followups">Follow Ups:</a><br>
<ul><!--insert: 908-->
</ul><!--end: 908-->
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
<a name="postfp">Post a Followup</a><p>
<form method=POST action="http://www.skeptic.com/cgi-local/skepticboard.pl">
<input type=hidden name="followup" value="728,774,855,903,908">
<input type=hidden name="origname" value="Carlos Javier">
<input type=hidden name="origemail" value="skeptic@mail.get.com.tw">
<input type=hidden name="origsubject" value="Re: The particular danger of some religions (Christianity and Islam)">
<input type=hidden name="origdate" value="January 06, 1997 at 22:14:03">
Name: <input type=text name="name" size=50><br>
E-Mail: <input type=text name="email" size=50><p>
Subject: <input type=text name="subject"value="Re: The particular danger of some religions (Christianity and Islam)" size=50><p>
Comments:<br>
<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: I'd say that we agree more than we disagree.  I do, however, take issue with the idea that I was making an ad hominem attack, as such things are repulsive to me.  Also, I would never say that atheists are communists; I might say that most communists are atheists or that the average communist is an atheist.  Give me a little credit for critical thinking, and please reread what I said about generalizations (about duly noting exceptions).

: We both see possible danger in certain religious tendencies, but we seem to disagree as to the extent of the danger or the likelihood that it will affect us infidels.  A friend and I are in a contrasting situation on another topic; he sees conscious conspiracies in government mistreatment of minorities, where I generally give the government less credit for cunning and forethought.

: As far as differences between Canucks and USians, don't get me started.  I grew up in Michigan.  We can start an e-mail chat about differences.  I feel they are insignificant, and are played up too much by nationalist Canadians who are tired of being mistaken for &quot;Americans&quot;.  But such a digression should be saved for e-mail.

</textarea>
<p>
