<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: Theory of Evolution in Jeopardy</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Theory of Evolution in Jeopardy</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:Lars.Berg@genetik.uu.se">Lars Berg</a> on December 18, 1996 at 16:47:45:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="536.html">Re: Theory of Evolution in Jeopardy</a> posted by Lynn on December 17, 1996 at 10:06:20:<p>
: <br>: : : Would anyone like to comment on the article from the Associated Press about new evidence that Homo erectus lived at the same time as modern humans?<p>: : No comment, just a question: in what way is the theory of evolution "jeopardized" by this evidence? I wouldn't say the theory hinges on the statement that H. erectus died out long before H. sapiens arrived.<p>: <br>: Hi Lars,<p>: Good to hear from you again.<p>: Perhaps I should have said that this puts the theory on the evolution of man in jeopardy.  Maybe things have changed, but when I was in school, we were shown a chart explaining how one hominid evolved into another, and that Homo erectus was an ancestor to modern man.  I suppose I don't understand how we evolved FROM Homo erectus if we both existed at the same time.    Please explain. <p>You may look at it this way, as an example: humans have produced many "races" of dogs by selective breeding, and the ultimate ancestors of all dogs were wolves (Canis lupus I believe). Now, just because their ancestors were also the ancestors of modern dogs, this does not mean that wolves could not continue to exist as long as the two lineages do not interbreed to any large extent. When lineages split evolution (i.e. adaptation and stochastic genetic changes) may allow them to become very different, but nothing says they cannot both continue to exist, nor that evolution must happen equally fast in both lineages.<p>By the way, the same misunderstanding have given rise to the misconception that humans are said to have evolved "from the apes". More correctly, evolutionary theory holds that humans evolved from the same ancestors as modern apes did. The difference seems slight but is significant.
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
