: You may look at it this way, as an example: humans have produced many &quot;races&quot; of dogs by selective breeding, and the ultimate ancestors of all dogs were wolves (Canis lupus I believe). Now, just because their ancestors were also the ancestors of modern dogs, this does not mean that wolves could not continue to exist as long as the two lineages do not interbreed to any large extent. When lineages split evolution (i.e. adaptation and stochastic genetic changes) may allow them to become very different, but nothing says they cannot both continue to exist, nor that evolution must happen equally fast in both lineages.

