<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: Theory of Evolution in Jeopardy</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Theory of Evolution in Jeopardy</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Lynn on December 17, 1996 at 10:06:20:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="535.html">Re: Theory of Evolution in Jeopardy</a> posted by Lars Berg on December 17, 1996 at 03:36:18:<p>
<br>: : Would anyone like to comment on the article from the Associated Press about new evidence that Homo erectus lived at the same time as modern humans?<p>: No comment, just a question: in what way is the theory of evolution "jeopardized" by this evidence? I wouldn't say the theory hinges on the statement that H. erectus died out long before H. sapiens arrived.<p><br>Hi Lars,<p>Good to hear from you again.<p>Perhaps I should have said that this puts the theory on the evolution of man in jeopardy.  Maybe things have changed, but when I was in school, we were shown a chart explaining how one hominid evolved into another, and that Homo erectus was an ancestor to modern man.  I suppose I don't understand how we evolved FROM Homo erectus if we both existed at the same time.    Please explain. 
<br>
