<input type=hidden name="origname" value="David">
<input type=hidden name="origsubject" value="Re: Theory of Evolution in Jeopardy">
<input type=hidden name="origdate" value="December 18, 1996 at 11:33:26">
Name: <input type=text name="name" size=50><br>
E-Mail: <input type=text name="email" size=50><p>
Subject: <input type=text name="subject"value="Re: Theory of Evolution in Jeopardy" size=50><p>
Comments:<br>
<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: : 
: : : : Would anyone like to comment on the article from the Associated Press about new evidence that Homo erectus lived at the same time as modern humans?

: : : No comment, just a question: in what way is the theory of evolution &quot;jeopardized&quot; by this evidence? I wouldn't say the theory hinges on the statement that H. erectus died out long before H. sapiens arrived.

: : 
: : Hi Lars,

: : Good to hear from you again.

: : Perhaps I should have said that this puts the theory on the evolution of man in jeopardy.  Maybe things have changed, but when I was in school, we were shown a chart explaining how one hominid evolved into another, and that Homo erectus was an ancestor to modern man.  I suppose I don't understand how we evolved FROM Homo erectus if we both existed at the same time.    Please explain. 

: Lynn,

: If you read the linked article in Lars's memo it will explain.  Evolution doesn't say that if you evolve from something that the thing you evolved from automatically dies out (unfortunately one of the popular misconceptions of evolution).  Many evolutionary studies take place on drosophilia (fruit flies) because they breed so quickly.  Just because they manage to breed (&quot;evolve&quot;) into different sorts of drosophilia it doesn't mean that the existing ones die out.

</textarea>
